defaultThe ongoing public 
defaultdialogue
default 
defaultaround cyclist safety has generated more heat than light. Much discussion of the topic seems to reflect a 
default“
defaultTwo Tribes
default”
default mentality: many drivers and cyclists alike perceive themselves as blamed and bullied, and in response have a
defaultdopted an entrenched approach to the 
defaultdebate. At the heart of this dichotomy lies both sides’ convictions that cyclist injuries are mainly ‘the 
defaultother guy’s fault’: many cyclists feel that drivers treat them with reckless contempt; many drivers have countles
defaults tales of cyclists who ignore the rules of the road; both sides are quick to accuse the other of aggressive and irresponsible behaviour. This febrile atmosphere has only increased with the recent tragic spate of cyclist deaths.
