defaultThis evidence deliberately includes all qualifying police attended incidents, even where the actual degree of injury inflicted was not 
defaultparticularly severe. About five-sixths of the casualties in these incidents were recorded as ‘Slight’; this classification includes injuries such as whiplash, shallow cuts, sprains, bruising and shock requiring roadside attention. This choice was made for 
defaultseveral reasons:
defaultUp to six contributory factors (CFs) can be recorded by a police officer who attended the scene of an injury crash
default, each related to a participant (vehicle, driver, rider, passenger or uninjured pedestrian). 
defaultIt is important to a
defaultppreciate that 
defaultCFs reflect the officer's opinion at time of reporting 
defaultand 
defaultmay not be the result of extensive investigation
default. Therefore, they 
defaultshould be regarded 
defaultonly 
defaultas a general guide
default to the factors most likely to feature in incidents, rather than a definit
defaultive explanation for them. However, in the last seven years attending officers have recorded CFs for 
defaultover nine hundred thousand
default injury crashes, making them by far the most extensive and inclusive basis for examining 
defaultthe issues which 
defaulttypically 
defaultprecipitate
default sy
defaultstem failure 
defaultand 
defaultresult in injury.
